sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE THE LEAD AFTER WINNING ON THE PITCH.
West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons took four for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take over the top spot in the County Championship.

Their stay at the top, however, may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in their match with Nottinghamshire, which was affected by rain.

After dispatching Somerset by 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings lead by 94 before being bowled out for 296, with England's Andy Caddick taking three for 83.
Having trailed by 213, Somerset started their second innings firmly before Simmons took over to dismiss them for 174.
Essex, however, look certain to regain top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them solid control in their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day needs, scored 158, his first century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took an 82-run lead in the first innings.

By the close Yorkshire had converted that advantage into 37 runs, but off-spinner Such had dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on to 119 for five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man dismissed by England, continued to silence his critics as after making four for 45 on Thursday, he made 80 not out on Friday in the Warwickshire match.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who made 70 as Surrey closed with 429 for seven, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire continued their chase for their first league title since 1936, reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in the second innings, and still 100 runs away from avoiding defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody took six for 82, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, led Derbyshire to 471 and a first innings lead of 233.
After the disappointment of their first day of play, which was badly affected by the weather, Kent turned up the heat and dismissed Nottinghamshire by 214 points.
They were held by Paul Johnson with 84 points, but former England Martin McCague got four points for 55.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER APPOINTED CAPTAIN OF ENGLAND.
The world's highest paid footballer, Alan Shearer, was named as England's new captain on Friday.

The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for 15 million pounds sterling ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team during the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer takes over the captaincy on a trial basis, but new manager Glenn Hoddle said he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not make the job his own.
"I'm sure there won't be a problem, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could do it, but when I spoke to Alan he was ready and really wanted to do it.
"In four days it is very difficult to come to a 100% conclusion on something like this...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the situation of the team, even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's attacking partner at Euro 96, Teddy Sheringham, withdrew from the squad with an injury on Friday.
He will most likely be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.
FOOTBALL - ROMANIA BEAT LITHUANIA IN AN UNDER-21 MATCH.
Romania beat Lithuania 2-1 (1-1 at half-time) in a European under-21 football match on Friday.
FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS BANNED AFTER VIOLENT INCIDENTS IN THE VOLGOGRAD.

Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during a 1-0 home defeat on Saturday, which ended Rotor's brief run as league leaders.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in empty stands on September 3.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup, was fined $1,000.
Despite the loss, Rotor are in a good position with 11 games to play in the league.
Volgograd are three points behind Alanya and two behind Dynamo Moscow, while they have one game in hand on the leaders and two on the Moscow club.
BOXING - THE PANAMANIAN ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS WITH THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran steps into the ring on Saturday in another attempt to maintain his long career.
Duran, 45, faces little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City, Panama.
The fight, Duran's first on home soil in 10 years, is being billed here as the "Return of the Legend" and Duran is still talking as if he is in his prime.
This race is to prepare me.
I'm not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the fighter recognize that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - light heavyweight, middleweight, middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he struggles, he is on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could undercut his status as one of the world's greatest boxers," said Panamanian Boxing Association president Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will secure him a rematch with Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho took a controversial points decision against Panamezzos in Atlantic City in June in a title fight.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN DO A DOUBLE UPSET UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of upsets at the U.S. Open.
Washington, ranked 11th, failed to repeat his miraculous comeback at Wimbledon as he lost to hot wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour and 51-minute battle on the Stadium court.
Next to the grandstand, 10th seed Rios lost to another Wimbledon-related player - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The mercurial left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although former champion Agassi, who was ranked sixth, had to break from a dangerous 3-6 0-4 deficit, winning 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who came back from 1-5, two sets down in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semifinals, looked poised for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, a winner two weeks ago in New Haven for his first professional title, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington came back.
"I kept telling myself, 'Keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept my cool and was proud of myself for that - normally I would have folded the tent and gone home."
The hard-hitting O'Brien, a former U.S. national champion at the collegiate level, dished out 17 aces to finally subdue a Washington that never said no.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game when Washington, after saving a break point with a winning forehand at the line, netted a backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan hit two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another backhand from 40-0.
"You just keep fighting and trying to get him to play a little bit.
I think he was a little tense at times," Washington said.
But I think he served pretty well when he needed to. "

Tarango, whose outburst at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and a suspension from this year's All-England Club tournament, argued with the calls and taunted fans in his spirited two-hour-and-24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
A raucous section supporting the distracted Chilean booed the short American, who got all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, who is ranked 104th in the league. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match was decided in the tie-break of the third set, which the American won 7-5 to the disappointment of the spectators.
"I love the world, even if it boos me every day.
It makes me high, it makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I played my best tennis in college when my fraternities were throwing beers.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I think that's not it.
I think I played very badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
The balls were going very fast.
I lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball as I see it during the day.
I play an American and that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the field. "
At the end of the match, Tarango sent sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then waved his body to a section supporting Rios in a mocking salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are openly cheering against me.
After I won, I thought I could give them a little flash. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL - RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leader at quarterback and one of the most athletic players to ever play center, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful Philadelphia fans who have supported me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I'm sad to leave, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and provided many great moments for Philadelphia fans and the entire NFL."
Cunningham, drafted in the second round in 1985, completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a contract as a broadcaster.
